[2] USA: case count
Date: Mon 5 Aug 2019 11:07 AM ET
Source: US News & World Report [edited]
https://www.usnews.com/news/health-news/articles/2019-08-05/measles-update-case-count-hits-1172


Measles cases tick up again. 30 states have seen measles cases so far this year [2019]
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
There have been 1172 measles cases in the US this year as of 1 Aug 2019, according to the latest update from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

The new total -- an increase of 8 cases since the tally reported last week -- represents the greatest number of measles cases in the US in a single year since 1992. Measles was declared eliminated in the US in 2000, but public health experts have warned the country could lose its elimination status if the number of cases continues to creep up.

As of 1 Aug 2019, there had been 124 hospitalizations for measles, while 64 people reported complications like pneumonia and encephalitis, brain inflammation that can be fatal.

The Philippine health authorities have launched a massive vaccination campaign aimed at vaccinating some 2000 children against measles every day. The country suffers from a serious outbreak of this disease.

"Measles can cause serious complications," the CDC says. The agency says that out of 1000 people with measles, between 1 and 3 will die.

So far, 30 states have seen measles cases this year [2019], while Washington state; El Paso County, Texas; Los Angeles County, California; Rockland County, New York; and New York City are currently experiencing outbreaks of the highly contagious viral infection.

"More than 75% of the cases this year [2019] are linked to outbreaks in New York and New York City," the CDC says. "Measles is more likely to spread and cause outbreaks in US communities where groups of people are unvaccinated."

Multiple outbreaks in recent months are tied to international travelers who brought the virus back to the US from countries like Israel, Ukraine, and the Philippines, the CDC says. The New York outbreaks, meanwhile, have been concentrated largely among Orthodox Jewish communities and have prompted officials to declare public emergencies, require vaccinations in some neighborhoods and implement a ban on unvaccinated minors in Orthodox Jewish schools known as yeshivas.

Lawmakers in New York and Washington have tightened exemptions to their vaccine laws in wake of the outbreaks, while other states have weighed similar measures.

[Byline: Gaby Galvin]

