[3] USA (San Diego County, California) ex Philippines
Date: Wed 7 Aug 2019
Source: KPBS, City News Service [edited]
https://www.kpbs.org/news/2019/aug/07/infant-san-diegos-first-confirmed-measles-case-yea/


The 1st case of measles this year [2019] in San Diego County has been confirmed in an 11-month-old child who recently traveled to the Philippines. The child might have exposed others to the disease at 2 Kaiser Permanente medical facilities in recent days, the county's Health and Human Services Agency [HHSA] announced [Wed 7 Aug 2019].

The infant, who was not immunized, is in the hospital, according to the HHSA.

The HHSA is working with Kaiser Permanente to identify and follow up with patients and staff who might have been exposed at those locations to determine if they've been vaccinated and assess their potential for developing measles.

[See source URL for locations and times of possible exposure.]

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[The child was just below the age when children generally receive their 1st vaccination, that is, children should get 2 doses of MMR (measles, mumps, rubella) vaccine, starting with the 1st dose at 12-15 months of age, and the 2nd dose at 4-6 years of age. But since the child traveled to the Philippines where measles incidence is high, it would have been wise to vaccinate prior to travel. All people traveling to countries with a high incidence of measles should check their vaccination status. - Mod.LK]

